Lucy's Warblers ( Oreothlypis luciae ), which expressed the weakest relationship between winter rainfall and nest timing, are short-distance migrants and among the last of the breeding species to arrive at our study sites in the spring. Lucy's Warbler was the sole species that  van Riper et al. (2014)  predicted would increase in number during future climate change events.  The delay in nest initiation dates that we observed is contrary to multiple examples from higher latitudes in North America and Europe, where scientists have found long-term trends of earlier nest timing in response to changing climate ( Brown et al. 1999 ,  Crick and Sparks 1999 ,  Dunn and Winkler 1999 ,  Both and Visser 2001 ,  Crick 2004 ); however, nesting delay supports the findings of  Fontaine et al. (2009)  for migratory passerine birds in southwestern North America. In the higher-latitude examples, earlier nest initiation dates were tied to increasing temperatures. Increasing temperatures also may have some effect on nest initiation in the Sonoran Desert, but the effects of temperature differences seem to be obscured by the stronger reverse effect of low rainfall. Investigators have found drought-related delay of nest initiation dates in other arid and semiarid habitats of North America ( Anderson and Anderson 1973 ,  Brown and Li 1996 ,  Johnson et al. 2002 ,  Morrison and Bolger 2002 ,  Chase et al. 2005 ,  Preston and Rotenberry 2006 ), perhaps representing a widespread and consistent response of birds nesting in ecosystems with low and infrequent precipitation.  In 2010, we found that experimentally delaying nest initiation, designed to match nest initiation dates observed during drought years, had negative consequences for the nesting success and productivity of our study species. Nest survival was highest early in the breeding season, a period during which treatment pairs were excluded from nesting. Treatment pairs were unable to compensate for these missed nesting opportunities due to low nest survival rates over the remainder of the nesting season.  The low nest success of our treatment nests mirrored the low nest success and productivity that we observed on the Chemehuevi Wash following dry winters. Late-nesting treatment pairs were exposed to higher rates of predation and nest parasitism than were the early-nesting control pairs. Delayed-nesting treatment pairs missed optimal March conditions for high nesting success, and were unable to overcome lost productivity due to continued low nest survival rates during the remainder of the nesting season.  Although we were unable to measure arthropod density, we performed our experiment following a wet winter season. Researchers have previously found arthropod density to track rainfall and thus primary production in the Chihuahuan Desert ( Whitford and Creusere 1977 ) and in southwestern California ( Bolger et al. 2005 ), suggesting that there would have been high primary production and high arthropod density in our study plots in 2010. While low food availability during drought years may result in delayed nest initiation, both Black-tailed Gnatcatchers and Verdins still nest even during the severest droughts. Given the wet conditions in 2010 and the ability of our study species to nest in drought conditions, we do not believe that food availability decreased dramatically enough during our 2&ndash;3 weeks of experimental delay to limit our delayed-nesting treatment pairs. Yet by delaying the first-egg dates of treatment pairs by only 2&ndash;3 weeks, we produced low nest survival and productivity rates in treatment pairs that were similar to rates observed during droughts in 2006 and 2007.  Food-resource mediation (driven by variation in rainfall) of avian reproductive success has been documented by several investigators in arid habitats ( Boag and Grant 1981 ,  Grant and Grant 1987 ,  Bolger et al. 2005 ,  Preston and Rotenberry 2006 ).  Morrison and Bolger (2002)  and  Chase et al. (2005)  found that predation could also mediate annual changes in reproductive success in Song Sparrows (  Melospiza melodia  ) and Rufous-crowned Sparrows (  Aimophila ruficeps  ), while  Littlefield (2009)  speculated that Curve-billed Thrashers (  Toxostoma curvirostre  ) may escape predation from snakes by nesting earlier in the season during wet winters. To our knowledge, our study is the first documentation of nest parasite&ndash;mediated variation in reproductive success driven by variation in rainfall.  Working in coastal chaparral habitats,  Morrison and Bolger (2002)  determined that reproductive success was predator-mediated in wet years and food resource&ndash;mediated in dry years. Central to their conclusion was their observation that their study species largely failed to nest during a drought in 1999, an observation again made by  Bolger et al. (2005)  for Rufous-crowned Sparrows and for three additional study species during a severe drought in 2002. In the Sonoran Desert, we found that some species forego breeding during extreme drought, but that foregoing nesting is rare. Instead, we observed that Sonoran Desert species tended to delay nest initiation to a degree that was linearly related to the severity of winter rainfall shortages. Thus, while food-resource limitation may mediate reproductive success if species forego nesting completely, predation and parasitism may mediate reproductive success during drought if species simply delay nest initiation. In the Sonoran Desert, we found delayed nest initiation much more common than a complete cessation of nesting.  Delayed nesting exposes species to higher levels of predation and parasitism which exist later in the breeding season and which are not experienced by early-nesting individuals during wet breeding seasons. Our 2010 experiment demonstrated that this delay in nesting can result in significant decreases in nesting success and reproductive output even in the midst of a wet breeding season. It appeared that predator density increased on our study plots as the breeding season progressed. Female Brown-headed Cowbirds (which are both nest predators and nest parasites) were not present until mid-April. Anecdotally, we observed higher numbers of Greater Roadrunners (  Geococcyx californianus  ) and Cactus Wrens ( Campylorhynchus brunneicapillus ) later in the season due to the presence of young individuals, and we frequently observed what appeared to be family units of Cactus Wrens systematically hunting for Black-tailed Gnatcatcher and Verdin nests in May, June, and July. In addition,  Morrison and Bolger (2002)  and  Littlefield (2009)  provide convincing arguments that snakes are more active later in the season. Interestingly, although  Chase et al. (2005 ; following  Chase &lsqb;2002&rsqb; ) suggested that decreased vegetative nest cover during dry seasons may contribute to nest failure, we found that nest cover significantly increased for both Black-tailed Gnatcatchers and Verdins over the course of the season, such that potential nest concealment was highest when nest survival was lowest (McCreedy and van Riper, in press). This trend toward greater concealment was driven by a shift by both species to building nests in dense desert mistletoe (  Phoradendron californicum  ) clumps as the season progressed.  In a similar fashion, first broods of Black-tailed Gnatcatchers escaped cowbird parasitism. Brown-headed Cowbirds have occupied southwestern North America only in the last 100&ndash;200 years ( Laymon 1987 ,  Lowther 1993 ), and it appears that they have not yet adapted their breeding phenology to maximize their exposure to early-nesting desert species of the Mojave and Sonoran Deserts ( Johnson and van Riper 2004 ). Assuming that female cowbirds began parasitizing nests immediately upon arrival in our study plots, Black-tailed Gnatcatcher clutches completed by March 20 would have either fledged or nearly fledged before losses to cowbird activity began. As days lost to drought-delay accumulate, so too do the number of days the nest will be exposed to female cowbirds. This dynamic may play a significant role in the reproductive success of many other open-cup nesting species in southwestern North America, particularly the residents and short-distance migrants that appear to be most sensitive to drought-caused nesting delay ( Johnson and van Riper 2004 ).  It thus benefits avian species in the Southwest to nest earlier in the season, particularly in systems without severe late-winter storms. Yet, in drought conditions, many bird species appear unable to nest early. This suggests that food limitation may inhibit early nest initiation in arid habitats following winter drought, a topic that begs further research given climate projections into the coming decades. While some species in the arid Southwest forgo nesting completely during drought, many others simply delay nesting, a strategy that may produce diminished reproductive returns. Additional pressure from Brown-headed Cowbird parasitism may render this strategy untenable in the future for open-cup nesting species that are frequent nest-parasite hosts.  We wish to express our deep thanks to Dr. James Weigand and the Bureau of Land Management's California State Office for assistance with study design. Paul Taillie, Leonard Warren, and Stella Moss provided invaluable assistance locating and monitoring nests in 2010. In addition, Stuart Johnston, Jora Rehm-Lorber, Karl Bardon, Eileen Mueller, Kelly Iknayan, Michelle Gibson, Caroline Ailanthus, James Campbell, and Kyle Horton located and monitored nests over several seasons. Lindsay Smythe and the Kofa National Wildlife Refuge assisted with nest monitoring and housing in 2009 and 2010. Drs. Bob Steidl, Courtney Conway, William Mannan, and James Weigand assisted with experimental design and manuscript review. Terry Shaffer and Abigail Darrah assisted with logistic-exposure analysis. Any use of trade, product, or firm names is for descr